#  14030120 - 2: Source Detection
One generally needs to identify astronomical sources in their data before they can perform photometry or
morphological measurements.

Source detection and image segmentation are two closely related but distinct tasks in image processing.
Source detection is the process of identifying individual objects or sources in an image.
The main difference between source detection and image segmentation is that source detection focuses on 
   identifying individual objects, while image segmentation focuses on dividing the image into homogeneous 
   regions.
      - Source detection is typically more computationally expensive than image segmentation
      - Source detection provides more detailed information about individual objects than image 
         segmentation. If you need to know the precise location, size, and shape of each object in an
         image, then source detection is the better choice.

